comment.body:
@Flyman: I don't know why you'd need full emulation though. Modern Virtualization utilizes more efficient methods to emulate old hardware/interfaces needed by OSs, like mapping them to their modern equivalent though this requires a CPU that supports Virtualization. Windows XP is perfectly supported by VMs like Virtualbox, and runs amazingly even on top of another OS. I boot Windows XP in VB and I get to the desktop in seconds even though I only gave it 1GB of RAM and a single CPU core. Pretty much the only thing that's a headache in a VM is running GPU intensive programs, but it sounds like you don't need that anyway.

I just don't get why you'd need to perfectly emulate an old chunk of hardware in order to run Windows XP well on a modern PC.

Though if you really want to fully emulate a x86 PC and run Windows XP on it, x86 emulators like [Bochs](http://bochs.sourceforge.net/) already exist. And people are even running Windows XP on their Android phones now.
